story:
@bill{Bill} and I took a Greyhound to New Hampshire that February vacation to catch up with @j{J} and go skiing for a weekend. I had just bought two tapes - #music/album{The Doors Greatest Hits} and Neil Young's #music/album{Live Rust} - both of which I brought with me and listened to on my Walkman.

I was already a big #music/artist{Neil} fan, and was most interested in tracking down Sugar Mountain, though I would have preferred the studio version, I just didn't know where to find it. The primary means for learning which songs were on which albums back then was studying the backs of the tapes on the racks at the stores, and as I only found out a year or so later, after acquiring Neil's #music/album{Decade}, a collection of his work spanning his first ten years as an artist, Sugar Mountain never appeared on any of his albums. By then it was moot, however, since Decade had the version I wanted.

#timeline/10th.grade #media/tape #media/cd #format/album.live #format/collection #player/walkman #player/boombox.88

@j{J} and I loved Guns 'n Roses. @jim{Jim} did too, after rejecting them initially, no matter that @magall{Magall} and I spent a bus ride to junior high one morning trying to convince him to like them. That was back when @leo{Leo} liked them as well - he was responsible for the copies I had of #music/album{Appetite} and #music/album{Lies}, albums I wouldn't let my @parents{parents} catch me with - but unlike the rest of us, he unashamedly bowed out upon hearing the #music/album{Use Your Illusions}.

At the height of Use Your Illusion hype the first two albums enjoyed a sort of Renaissance, at least amongst my friends. @j{J} and I would sound the opening guitar riff to the slow version of You're Crazy often, akin to movie quoting, primary means of communication at that age. We went on to develop alt lyrics for that and other GNR gems, referring to our art as "canciones," an homage to the Spanish classes we were getting more out of than we realized.

#timeline/10th.grade #media/tape.blank #format/album #player/boombox.88 #almost.current

@mike{Mike} and @steve{Steve} split rooms when @pete{Pete} moved into the basement with me, and in the breakup the record player moved to the room at the opposite end of the upstairs. That's where I fell hard for Jefferson Airplane. #music/album{The Worst Of} was another survivor from my @parents{parents'} collection.

Liner notes would ultimately serve as a checklist for albums I needed to track down, excepting #music/album{Surrealistic Pillow}, another surviving record. I ended up drawing a particular image of Grace from its album art a number of times over the next few years, including in black marker on a pull-down window shade @leo{Leo} asked me to decorate for him.

#timeline/10th.grade #media/record #format/greatest.hits #player/record.player.toy

@jim{Jim} and I grew up on Led Zeppelin together. We eventually imagined that to live through #music/artist{Pearl Jam} releases was to live through Led Zeppelin releases--the next generation wishes they saw what we did.  He got #music/album{Physical Graffiti} first and I borrowed it at some point, but before that he played it for me on a trip to Starland in "the green machine," the Aries station wagon he inherited.

By the time we arrived we had only heard a track and a half, because #music/song{In The Light} and #music/song{Down By The Seaside} were so long, but on the ride back we got to Ten Years Gone, which blew those two and most of the rest of the album away. That tape played in his car for the rest of the summer, most notably to and from double session football practices.

#timeline/high.school.summers #media/tape #format/album #player/car.jim.green.machine

@maura{Maura} and I danced to Crazy For You at the Key Club karaoke dance that November. We began dating the following year and it went on to become our song. When making a tape for her some time later I wanted to include it, and so I ended up calling a bunch of girls from our class to track down the right Madonna tape.

That turned out to be the easy part. I ended up needing to shorten one side of that tape by about ten seconds, which meant I had to tape the last few songs over each other and closer together each time several times to get it to fit perfectly. A cliche, yes, but rewarding nonetheless.

#timeline/11th.grade #media/tape.blank #format/mix.given

@missy{Missy} invited me to the junior prom because @luke{Luke} told her to, and I was supposed to get him a date to the senior prom. I failed. In my final hours I tried desperately to work a plan to get @maura{Maura} to take him and I would take whoever he wanted, but if it was the thought that counted, I already blew it.

In any event, I had a lot of fun fulfilling Luke's end of the bargain. Late in the evening, Missy revealed she had made a tape for me to listen to on the plane trip to Colorado, which I regarded then as just about the sweetest thing anybody had ever done for me. The tape consisted mostly of 80s songs, and Broken Wings became one of two songs I listened to on repeat in the red Dodge Shadow after discovering its song seek feature, which magically found where songs on tapes started.

#timeline/12th.grade #media/tape.blank #format/mix.received #player/car.red.shadow

@elyse{Elyse} had left a mix of her own in my car years prior, the final song on which was #music/song{Wade In The Water}, a traditional song by some artist neither of us could identify. My mission to find out who it was lasted longer than such missions can last anymore, Internet and all. The Internet was sort of around then too, but the problem with this particular song was that it had been done by a hundred or more artists, so which was the right version ?

After working through eBay and finding the incorrect adaptation, I eventually returned to allmusic.com - and then to Newbury Comics - to determine the artist was named Ellen McIlwaine. I also determined there were other songs on her CD I was interested in, like All To You.

#timeline/watertown.1 #media/cd #format/collection #player/stereo.3.disc

@laura{Laura} and I went to visit @pete{Peter} on the Cape. He had a satellite radio receiver affixed to his kitchen window, the only place I'd ever seen satellite anywhere but in a car. During that visit Laura and I heard Maps by The Yeah Yeah Yeahs for the first time, a surprise to Pete since he thought it was already popular.

Of course, following the script, we heard the song again just minutes after leaving, and called Pete from the car to share.

#timeline/allston #media/radio.satellite.once #media/radio #player/car.sitting.bull

@bruce{Bruce} and I shared an appreciation for #music/artist{Neil}, who along with #music/artist{Frank Zappa} and Todd Rundgren represented his heroes, by his own proclamation. Following the logic, I borrowed the first Todd Rundgren album from him.

I already knew #music/song{Saw The Light} and #music/song{Hello It's Me}, but Rundgren clearly had more dimension. I loved the part in I Went To The Mirror when he's singing about "the first thing to come into focus," how the music makes that great warping sound, suggestive of the mirror imagery he's singing about.

#timeline/allston #media/cd #format/album #player/computer.work.linux #work #borrowed

@toland{John} was in town, and had planned a gathering at @shawn{Shawn} and @alicia.w{Alicia's} house in Quincy. @laura{Laura} and I went, but I disappeared for a while to play in a card game at @marc{Johnson's} two towns over. I was intent on playing liberally, given I had a backup plan, and sure enough I was out in two hands, on my way back to hang out with everybody.

Earlier that day Laura's grandfather had died. It wasn't unexpected, but I didn't know how it would affect her. During that ride back to Quincy, I became acutely focused on her loss, wondering how she'd be later, the weight of implications lending power to the experience. I listened only to the The Beekeeper for the duration of that ride, infusing its textures into the memory indelibly.

#timeline/the.dike #media/cd #player/car.laura.altima #player/stereo.laura.dane #borrowed

@cate{Cate} and @q{Rob} both said All For Leyna was their favorite Billy Joel song, and so one of them dropped the track in their home directory at work for me to listen to, part of an effort to convince me to get on board with covering it in an ITA band project. @bruce{Bruce}, @wendi{Wendi}, myself and maybe others participated in a few practices in the unfinished space on 7, but the project never manifested.

As for All For Leyna, I had never heard it before--#music/album{Glass Houses} must have been one of the few Billy Joel albums @pete{Peter} didn't have as a kid. I ended up liking it quite a bit, though.

#timeline/the.beak #media/file #player/computer.work.linux

@boogie{Brendan} was playing the Rumble with #music/artist{Scamper}, and I went to see him, earning myself an introduction to The Campaign For Real Time, also playing. I think they might have even won it that year, but whatever happened, they can take credit for introducing a new mode of music take to my life: myspace.

I remember asking @luke{Luke} shortly thereafter if anybody had ever suggested their singer sounded like him. I thought he did.

#timeline/maynard.1 #media/myspace #player/computer.work.linux

@spoth{Spoth} had said in a previous year that Arcade Fire was his favorite band going, but I guess it took me until they went mainstream to start paying attention. I just hadn't heard enough, and hadn't fallen for what little I'd heard.

It was their performance to close out the Grammy's that year that changed me, not just on music, but on life. Their exhibition of creativity, with everybody running around that stage, demure fashion sense, energy, enthusiasm, dude with a megaphone--it engendered a steady and determined sobriety in me. I wanted to dedicate myself to creativity too.

#timeline/maynard.2 #media/tv.performance #media/itunes #media/cd.burned #format/album #player/tv #player/laptop.11 #player/car.laura.altima

@greg{Greg's} 35th birthday party at his upstate New York home was a highlight of the year. Indeed, the game in the foyer, involving a mini beach ball, counting @alison.j{Alison}, @faust{Faust}, and myself among its participants, that @laura.k{Laura} still doesn't know about, engendered what may have been my hardest laughs that year. It was just so hilarious that, no matter how hard we tried, none of us could elevate the ball above waist level. Too many frantic hands converging to slap it away, attempting to gain control themselves, a process that repeated over and over again in rapid succession.

Before that, on the ride out there, I picked up @mike{Mike} at the Albany airport, at which point I was fully wrapped up in Coldplay #music/album{X + Y}, which for some reason resurfaced in @laura{Laura's} car that I was borrowing (must have been due to the shuffle in moving from Maynard to Kingston), and which for some reason I had never gotten into fully before.

#timeline/kingston.1 #media/cd #format/album #player/car.laura.altima

@bairdo{Bairdo}, @shawn{Shawn}, @billy.t{Billy T}, and I drove together the @toland{John's} bachelor party on the Jersey Shore that @paul{Paul} had set up for about ten or fifteen of us that spring. The first night, after sleeping on the floor for about an hour, it was 10AM -- time to get started again. 

Onto the second story front porch, where I encountered John's cousin @ritchie{Ritchie}, carrying around and listening to his own old school boombox. When Get Lucky came blasting out of the speakers, he got so excited, as if it wasn't his own mix he was listening to, even though it was. With a big smile and a sort of head bobbing dance, he was rallying my enthusiasm for a song I had never heard before. I did, however, hear it a dozen more times that weekend, and tons more after that when it became so popular. Brings me back to that weekend and Ritchie's positive energy every time.

#timeline/kingston.1 #media/radio #player/boombox #player/car.black.prius #popular

@leo{Leo} gets all the credit for turning me onto #music/album{Yeesus}, the latest from Kanye. I hadn't been following along at all, never knew much about Kanye besides his few radio hits, but for Yeesus I was all in. Only after that did I dig into the older stuff, much the way things went for me with #music/artist{Radiohead} and #music/album{Kid A}. 

At work, @jd{JD} somehow figured out what I was listening to, and from then on referred to Kanye as "your boy" whenever we talked about him. We went on to argue about the merits of his new music versus his old, me still favoring the former, the older stuff still relatively unfamiliar to me. That was about to change.

#timeline/kingston.1 #media/spotify #format/album #player/laptop.work.mac #current

@luke{Luke} and I got to talking about music at a bar downtown during @steveo{Steveo's} bachelor party a couple years prior. He mentioned a new bunch of bands making music similar to the wave of "alternative" bands from when we were in high school. A couple years later, the only one I could remember he mentioned was #music/artist{Yuck}. I gave them a shot, and from there randomly meandered to a few artists that would come to represent my spring and summer that year, especially two: #music/artist{Real Estate} and Lotus Plaza. 

As for Lotus Plaza's top track Strangers, I wanted to let them know it was in consideration for a spot in my ten favorite songs in the world.

#timeline/kingston.2 #media/spotify #format/playlist #player/laptop.work.mac

@laura{Laura}, @sid{Sid}, @annie{Annie}, and I went to Coastal Maine for our family vacation that summer. We heard #music/song{Dead Fox} on the hip local radio station while riding around and more fully discovered Courtney Barnett when we got back to the house. She was the artist of the week for certain, the month most likely and even the year perhaps. The radio once pitched that she was receiving hype as the Australian #music/artist{Bob Dylan} -- I was thrilled somebody would take it that far.

@patb{Pat} and @eli{Eli} gave me a ride home after the end of the season ultimate tournament that August. We talked about their imminent wedding and also what music we were listening to. Pat mentioned #music/artist{Deer Tick}. I mentioned Courtney Barnett.

#timeline/kingston.3 #media/spotify #format/album #player/laptop.work.mac #current

@bill{Bill} and I, after a long hiatus concurring on music, made a plan to make each other a mix of what we were listening to at the time. How Big, How Blue, How Beautiful was my Florence entrant from her latest album.

The next year, upon arrival at @bugbee{Bugbee's} going away to Arizona party, it was a rush to realize this was the song playing on their sound system. A small amount of investigation concluded @kat.b{Kat} was responsible.

#timeline/kingston.3 #media/spotify #format/album #format/playlist #format/mix.given #player/laptop.work.mac #current

@laura{Laura} borrowed a themed playlist from the playlist gods and let it run from the computer in the kitchen. I dragged Out To Sea by Lera Lynn into a playlist for myself when I heard it there, but didn't give it a great deal of attention initially. I didn't even realize that Lera Lynn was the artist on the stage throughout the second season of True Detective, which we had seen a year or so prior.

I started piecing it all together later that year when I fell head over heels for Lera Lynn. Out To Sea had that beauty-in-sadness quality, and a crushing amount of it, putting it into the same echelon as #music/song{Mouthful of Cavities} (Blind Melon) and Coldplay's #music/song{Amsterdam}.

